                                 <p id="p0">The Waist to Front Fork measurement is taken similarly to the Waist to Waist measurement with the exception of stopping midway through the crotch curve. Take the tape measure from CF at waist level, through the legs and pressing the tape measure towards the front of your perineum. Pinch the tape at the spot in which was indicated to be forward of the perineum and remove the tape from between the legs, record the measurement where the tape is pinched.  </p> &nbsp; 
                                 <p id="p0">As an additional visualization to identify where the Front Crotch Curve should end, think where the forked seam of a pair of fitted jeans would sit or the middle of your inseam if you were to divide your inner leg in half. 


                                     <br> &nbsp;</p>
                                     <p id="p0">The Waist to Front Fork is the measurement that will determine the proportion of the Waist to Waist measurement to be allocated for the front panel and thus the back panel. By measuring from Center Front Waist to the front of the perineum, we are measuring the length of the front crotch curve. Since the body typically carries more girth in the back than the front, there will be a greater proportion of the Waist to Waist that must be allocated to the back. However, the allocation of the Waist to Waist to front and back is specific to each individual. 
